\section{Old School}

We play classic D\&D using rules from the early
eighties.\marginnote{Ownership of the rules is optional. If you want
  to dig deeper, I recommend
  \href{http://www.rpgnow.com/product/110274/DD-Basic-Set-Rulebook-B-X-ed-Basic}{Basic D\&D by Moldvay} and
  \href{http://www.rpgnow.com/product/110792/DD-Expert-Set-Rulebook-B-X-ed-Basic}{Expert D\&D by Cook}.

  My campaigns are usually limited to ten levels which is why the
  information for higher level player characters is missing. If you
  need suggestions, I suggest going back to
  \href{http://www.goblinoidgames.com/labyrinthlord.html}{Labyrinth Lord}.}
The rules offer \textbf{very little mechanics}: there aren't many
classes to choose from, no feats, no skills, no prestige classes and
hardly any special abilities, no magic items for sale. Furthermore,
elves, dwarves and halflings are simply separate classes. There are no
elven thieves or dwarven mages. On the other hand, fewer rules also
leave \textbf{a lot of freedom} for players. The characters are as
diplomatic, friendly or intimidating as the players want them to be.

There are \textbf{no clerics} in my game and I use \textbf{restricted
  spell acquisition} for magic users: finding scrolls and spellbooks
will not allow you to master those spells. You need a teacher until
you reach level nine.\marginnote{That's when you get to
  \hyperref[key:Research]{research} new spells.}

We're playing in a
\href{http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/WideOpenSandbox}{sandbox}.
There is \textbf{no planned ending} for the campaign. The actions of
player characters determines the directions the campaign grows
in.\marginnote{Players determine where the campaign will head. If
  player characters investigate rumors and locations, I will develop
  the game world in that direction. The harder you look, the more
  there is to see.}

Dangers are not adapted to the strength of the party. Generally
speaking it's safer near civilized settlements. The further you move
into the wilderness, the more dangerous it is. That's how
\textbf{players control the risks they want to take}.

Preparation and experience should help you avoid situations, where
your character's survival depends on a single die roll.\marginnote{The
  game will remain dangerous for a long time. At very low levels
  limited hit points mean you'll die if you get hit. Later, around
  level five and six, it's still easy to die because of spells like
  \emph{fireball} or \emph{lightning bolt}, poisonous critters and
  petrifying gazes, or level drain. At higher level, when the first
  characters hit level eight and nine, the game will be less dangerous
  and involve more reaction rolls and larger battles, but then again,
  the characters will soon retire from adventuring…} If you're rolling
dice, it's already too late. \textbf{A saving throw is your last
  chance} to survive due to luck and experience. Ideally you would
never have to roll dice because you're well informed and equipment.
Perseus didn't have to save against the medusa's petrifying gaze
because \emph{he was well prepared}.

\textbf{Retainers are another safeguard against character death}:
torch bearers, porters, men-at-arms and mercenaries all cost money,
but they will also keep your character alive. Should player characters
die, the next character is most probably going to be one of their
retainers.

\textbf{Experience points} are gained by \textbf{spending gold} you
gained on adventures.\marginnote{Spending gold on public
  \hyperref[sec:buildings]{buildings} is one way of spending a lot of
  money.} If you manage to obtain the gold without combat, good for
you. The best strategy is to pick your battles and stake the odds in
your favor as far as possible. Remember, if you're rolling dice, it's
already too late.

