\section{\index{Movement}Movement}
\label{sec:movement}

\key{Movement Rate}: Humans have a movement rate (\key{MV}) of
12---that's \unit[120]{ft} per round (\unit[10]{s}) when
\emph{running} or \emph{fighting}. \marginnote[-1em]{Typical movement
  rates of other creatures: dwarf 6, halfling 9, elf 12, giant weasel
  15, dog or wolf 18, panther 21, galloping horse 24, flying
  hippogryph 36, flying pegasus 48.}

Proceeding slowly and methodically in the underworld slows you down
dramatically. MV~12 is only \unit[120]{ft} per turn (\unit[10]{min}).
That's the only way to have a fair chance of drawing maps and avoiding
traps.

\key{Carrying Capacity}: You can carry as many significant items as
your \emph{strength}.\marginnote{Typical items: armor, a weapon, a
  book, a potion, a torch, a quiver, a scroll. There's no difference
  between light and heavy items. Clothing, bags or backpacks don't
  count.} If you carry more, each extra item adds -1 to hit and to
saving throws.

\key{Stuff}: It takes a lot of small things to count as an item: a
hundred gold coins, gems, rings, amulets and the like count as a
single item.

